# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] An expedition led by Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Charles Wentworth in 1813 was the first recorded crossing of the Blue Mountains in New South Wales.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The crossing enabled the settlers to access and use the land west of the mountains for farming, and made possible the establishment of Australia's first inland colonial settlement at Bathurst.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The European settlement at Sydney Cove, established in 1788 after the arrival of the First Fleet, grew rapidly.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] By the early 19th century, the Blue Mountains had become a barrier to the expansion of the colony, which required more farming land to meet its needs, particularly after the droughts of 1812 and 1813.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The local indigenous people knew at least two routes by which to cross the mountains.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The first was along Bilpin Ridge, later followed by Archibald Bell with the assistance of the local Darug people (now the location of Bells Line of Road), and the second was along Coxs River.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Until 1813 however, the settlers remained unaware of how to cross the mountains despite several attempts, including two by Blaxland himself.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Early in 1813 Blaxland, who wanted more grazing land, obtained the approval of Governor Lachlan Macquarie and approached Lawson and Wentworth to secure their participation in a new exploratory expedition following the mountain ridges.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Gregory Blaxland was born on 17 June 1778 in Kent, England.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He sailed for Australia on 1 September 1805 with his wife, three children, two servants, an overseer, a few sheep, seed, tools, groceries, and clothing.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] When he reached Sydney he sold many of these items and made a profit which enabled him to buy eighty head of cattle so that he could breed cattle and sell the meat.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He located 1,600 hectares of land that the government had promised to new settlers as well as forty convict servants and established his farm.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He was also one of the first people to plant grapes in Australia and make wine, for which he was awarded a silver medal and later a gold one from the Royal Society of Arts, London.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The town of Blaxland is named after him.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] William Lawson was born in England, where he later trained to become a surveyor.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He migrated to Sydney, Australia, arriving in 1800.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He was an officer in the New South Wales Corps and owned land where he raised many cattle and sheep.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] He was invited to join the 1813 expedition with Gregory Blaxland.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] William Charles Wentworth was born in Australia to Irish parents.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] In 1802 he was sent to school in England and returned to Sydney in 1810, where he worked for the governor, Lachlan Macquarie, and was given a land grant of 708.2 hectares (1,750 acres) on the Nepean River.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The town of Wentworth Falls is named after him.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Blaxland, Wentworth and Lawson led an expedition party, which included four servants, four pack horses and five dogs.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Two of the four men who assisted the party have been identified as James Burne (or Burnes), a guide and kangaroo hunter, and Samuel Fairs, a convict who arrived in Australia in 1810.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The two others, also thought to be convicts, remain unidentified.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The party left from Blaxland's South Creek farm near the modern suburb of St Marys in western Sydney, on 11 May 1813 and crossed the Nepean River later that day.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] They made their way over the mountains, following the ridges, and completed the crossing in 21 days.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The explorers' success has been attributed to their methodical approach and decision to travel on the ridges instead of through the valleys.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The three explorers and two of their servants would set out each day, leaving the other two men at their campsite, and mark out a trail, before turning back later in the day to cut a path for the horses and allow the rest of the party to progress.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The group first saw the plains beyond the mountains from Mount York.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] They continued on to Mount Blaxland 25 km south of the site of Lithgow, on the western side of the mountains.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] From this point Blaxland declared there was enough forest or grassland "to support the stock of the colony for thirty years", while Lawson called it "the best watered Country of any I have seen in the Colony".
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The party then turned back, making the return journey in just six days.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] All three explorers wrote an account of their expedition.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Blaxland was the only one to publish his account, *Journal of a Tour of Discovery Across the Blue Mountains*, which he did in 1823 during a return visit to England.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Lawson, as a trained surveyor, kept detailed notes about the route itself including the distances covered each day, as well as his impressions of the landscape.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] In recognition of the successful crossing, all three explorers were rewarded by Macquarie with a grant of 1000 acres of land west of the mountains.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Blaxland later claimed to have led the expedition; however, records from the time of the crossing imply that they were joint leaders.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Surveyor-General George William Evans was dispatched by Macquarie in November 1813 to follow the path taken and travel further to determine the best route to access the arable farmland.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Evans continued past Mount Blaxland to the Macquarie and Lachlan Rivers and the site of modern Bathurst.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Upon his return, he was rewarded with 1000 acres of land in Tasmania.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Macquarie then commissioned William Cox in July 1814 to construct a road, following the path taken by the three explorers and extended by Evans.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Cox's team of convict workers completed the job in six months and Cox was rewarded by Macquarie with a grant of 2000 acres of land near the site chosen by Macquarie for Bathurst.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Macquarie travelled along the new road, naming it the Great Western Road, in 1815.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] Artist John Lewin accompanied Macquarie on the tour.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] The colonial expansion into the lands of the Wiradjuri people, west of the Blue Mountains, led to the Bathurst war.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] It has been claimed that Blaxland, Wentworth and Lawson may have carved their initials into the tree now referred to as the Explorers tree, located about 5 kilometres west of Katoomba.
[src:australia/1813-crossing-of-the-blue-mountains] This claim is not universally supported and the tree is not specifically mentioned in the journals kept by the explorers, although they did mark trees to record their route.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] A series of referendums on the proposed constitution of Australia were held between 2 June 1898 and 31 July 1900 in the six colonies that were to become the states of the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The first four referendums were held in New South Wales, South Australia, Tasmania and Victoria in June 1898.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Although all four saw a majority vote in favour, the majority in New South Wales was insufficient.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Knowledge of the result in New South Wales led to low voter turnout in South Australia.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Following a series of amendments made to the proposed constitution at the Secret Premiers meeting on 31 January and 1 February 1899, a second referendum was required in the four states, whilst on 2 September, Queensland held a referendum on the constitution for the first time.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] All five states saw a majority vote in favour.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Three weeks after the Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act became law in 1900, Western Australia held a referendum on the constitution, which was also approved.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The constitution came into force on 1 January 1901.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Following the National Australasian Convention in 1891, support for federalism reduced in the face of opposition from George Reid and the sudden advent of the Labor Party in NSW, which commonly dismissed federation as a "fad".
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] However, a subsequent revival of the federal movement owed much to the growth of federal leagues outside of capital cities, and, in Victoria, the Australian Natives' Association.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The Border Federation League of Corowa held a conference in 1893 which was to prove of considerable significance, and a "People's Convention" in Bathurst in 1896 underlined the cautious conversion of George Reid to the federal cause.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] At the close of the Corowa Conference John Quick had advanced a scheme of a popularly elected convention, tasked to prepare a constitution, which would then be put to a referendum in each colony.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Winning the support of George Reid, the new premier of NSW, the Quick scheme was approved by all premiers in 1895.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] After the Adelaide meeting, the colonial Parliaments took the opportunity to debate the emerging Bill and to suggest changes.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The basic principles of the 1891 draft constitution were adopted, modified by a consensus for more democracy in the constitutional structure.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] It was agreed that the Senate should be chosen, directly, by popular vote, rather than appointed by State governments.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] On other matters there was considerable disagreement.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] 'Interests' inevitably fractured the unity of delegates in matters involving rivers and railways, producing legalistic compromises.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] And they had few guides, at a conceptual level, to what they were doing.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Deakin greatly praised James Bryce's sage appreciation of American federalism, *The American Commonwealth*.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] And Barton cited the analysis of federation of Bryce's Oxford colleagues, E.A.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] But neither of these two writers could be said to be actual advocates of Federation.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] And for delegates less given to reading (or citing) authors, the great model of plural governance was always the British Empire, which, obviously was no federation at all.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The Australasian Federal Convention dissolved on 17 March 1898 having adopted a bill "To Constitute the Commonwealth of Australia".
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Referendums on the proposed constitution were held in four of the colonies in June 1898.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] There were majority votes in all four, however, the enabling legislation in New South Wales required the support of at least 80,000 voters for passage, equivalent to about half of enrolled voters, and this number was not reached.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] A meeting of the colonial premiers in early 1899 agreed to a number of amendments to make the constitution more acceptable to New South Wales.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] In June 1899, referendums on the revised constitution were again held again in all the colonies except for Western Australia, where the vote was not held until the following year.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The majority vote was "yes" in all the colonies.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] Residents of South Australia were staunchly opposed to federation in the mid-19th century due to the dominance of the colonies of Victoria and New South Wales in issues such as trade and tariffs, as well as a desire to keep unique elements of South Australia intact.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The mood had shifted by the 1890s, with what was seen as the looming inevitability of federation a motivator to negotiating a good deal for the less populous colonies, with the argument by the Yes campaign that they may never have such favourable terms again.
[src:australia/1898-1900-australian-constitutional-referendums] The No campaign however focused on the potential for increased costs for South Australians, as well as decreased land values.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:australia/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] After World War II, membership of the Communist Party of Australia had peaked at around 20,000 and Fred Paterson had won the seat of Bowen in the 1944 Queensland state election.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Communists became prominent in trade unions as well as cultural and literary circles.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Following the attempted nationalisation of the Australian Banks in 1948, Opposition Leader Robert Menzies became concerned that communist ideas were infiltrating the Labor Party.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] A Queensland rail strike in that same year cemented that idea.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Menzies vowed that if elected he would outlaw communism.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] On 27 June 1949, coal miners went out on strike, supported by the Communist Party and various unions.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Bargaining quickly broke down between the unions and government and on 1 August, Prime Minister Chifley sent in troops from the Australian Armed Forces to run the mines until the dispute was resolved.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] By its fourth day, the Sydney docks were congested with coal ships unable to leave the port, the loading of ships being severely delayed by restricted transport.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] By 1 July the government was examining the possibility of importing coal from Britain.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The strike lasted over 6 weeks, until 15 August.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Later that year, PM Chifley also brought in legislation to begin the rationing of petrol.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Both of these events became key issues in the 1949 federal election campaign.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] During the campaign, Menzies asserted that socialism was the "outstanding issue" of the day.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] He accused the Labor Party of having communist leanings, citing as proof its banking legislation and regulation in other areas of the economy.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] "A vote for Labor," he suggested, "is a vote for the socialist objective".
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Socialism was, according to Menzies, detrimental to the freedom and prosperity of the nation, and to be considered a real and prominent threat to the Australian way of life.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] In December 1949, the Liberal Party with Robert Menzies as Prime Minister won a majority in the House of Representatives with 74 of 121 seats.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] On 23 June 1950, the *Communist Party Dissolution Bill 1950* (Cth) was introduced.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] In his speech introducing the Bill, PM Menzies read out the names of 53 members of the Communist Party of Australia, referring to them as a "traitorous minority" which threatened the security of the nation.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The Bill passed the House of Representatives, but struggled to pass the Senate, which had a Labor party majority.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Labor senators agreed that the Communist Party should be dissolved, but held reservations about allowing the Governor-General in Council (the executive government) to 'declare' people communists.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] These reservations were especially strong after Menzies admitted that the names of Communist Party members which had been read out on the House floor contained errors.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Amendments were proposed that removed this power, but the Labor Party later withdrew its opposition and the Bill passed the Senate without amendments on 19 October 1950.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] It was brought into effect as the *Communist Party Dissolution Act 1950* (Cth) on 20 October 1950.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Such persons were not allowed to be employed by the Commonwealth in public service, or in industries considered vital to the defence of Australia.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] They were not permitted to run for office and were prohibited from joining a union.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The Communist Party of Australia was declared an unlawful organisation and was dissolved, its property forfeited to the Commonwealth without compensation.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Affiliated organisations were also liable to be declared unlawful, at the government’s discretion.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Immediately following the passage of the Act, a challenge was filed in the High Court.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The case was heard beginning on 14 November 1950 by all seven judges of the High Court.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The question was whether the federal government had the power to pass this law under the Section 51(vi) of the Constitution of Australia (also known as the *defence power*).
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Section 51(vi) of the Constitution gives the Parliament power to make laws in regard to "the naval and military defence of the Commonwealth and of the several States, and the control of the forces to execute and maintain the laws of the Commonwealth".
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The Commonwealth claimed that the Act was valid under this power because communists presented a real threat to Australian security, as revolution was a central theme of marxism.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] On 19 March 1951, the Court ruled 6:1 (Latham CJ dissenting) that the Act was invalid.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] A referendum was called on 23 August 1951, which sought to insert a clause into the constitution that empowered the Federal Parliament make laws in reference to communism and communists.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Newspaper editorials were overwhelmingly in favour of the ban with 12 editorials in support, two papers not taking a stance (*Daily Mirror* and *Daily News*), and just one newspaper against it (*The Argus*).
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The Labor party had decided to campaign for a No vote despite supporting the Bill through the senate the previous year.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Opposition Leader HV Evatt held more speeches than Menzies and started campaigning earlier, campaigning vigorously against what he perceived as Menzies' attempt to establish a police state in Australia.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Menzies' speeches were often interrupted by the No campaign's hecklers, although Menzies claimed to have been happy with the uproar because it demonstrated the communists' "disrespect for Liberal norms".
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Some Liberal Party members and non-affiliated conservatives also supported the No campaign, which undermined Menzies efforts to convince the public that this was a necessary measure.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Despite this, seven weeks before the ballot, the ban was supported by 73.3% percent of respondents in a Gallup Poll.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The reason behind the Gallup support plummeting for Yes has been estimated to have been especially middle class Liberal voters slipping away from the Coalition position, whereas Labor kept their ranks better.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Bi-partisan support was usually required for constitutional amendments to pass in Australia.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The referendum was held on 22 September 1951.
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] Reflecting on the outcome, Menzies remarked "to get an affirmative vote from the Australian people on a referendum proposal is one of the labours of Hercules".
[src:australia/1951-australian-communist-party-ban-referendum] The 'Constitutional Alteration (Power to deal with Communists and Communism) 1951' proposed to insert into the constitution after section 51 the following text.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:australia/1956-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
[src:australia/au] The domain name was originally allocated by Jon Postel, operator of the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to Kevin Robert Elz of Melbourne University in 1986.
[src:australia/au] After an approximately five-year process in the 1990s, the Internet industry created a self-regulatory body called .au Domain Administration (auDA) to operate the domain.
[src:australia/au] It obtained assent from ICANN in 2001, and commenced operating a new competitive regime for domain registration on 1 July 2002.
[src:australia/au] Since this new regime, any registration has to be ordered via a registrar.
[src:australia/au] Oversight of .au is by auDA, a not-for-profit organisation whose membership is derived from Internet organisations, industry members and interested individuals.
[src:australia/au] The organisation operates with the endorsement of the Australian Government and with the delegated authority of ICANN.
[src:australia/au] Policy for .au is devised by policy development panels.
[src:australia/au] These panels are convened by auDA and combine public input with industry representation to derive policy.
[src:australia/au] The day-to-day operation of the .au registry technical facility is tendered out by auDA.
[src:australia/au] AusRegistry has performed the registry role since the initial tender in 2002.
[src:australia/au] In December 2017, Afilias won a competitive tender process to take over the running of the registry from AusRegistry.
[src:australia/au] The registry does not sell domain registration services direct to the consumer, rather consumers who wish to register a domain must do so via a domain name registrar.
[src:australia/au] After the industry's liberalisation in 2002, there is an active competitive market in registrars with a variety of prices and services.
[src:australia/au] In 2008, auDA changed its longstanding policy and allowed changes in ownership of .au domains.
[src:australia/au] Although the secondary market was initially slow to take off, there have recently been signs of increasing maturity in the .au aftermarket culminating in the record $125,500 sale of investmentproperty.com.au.
[src:australia/au] The auDA information security standard (ISS) is an industry initiative aimed at improving the security of .au registrar businesses, protecting .au registrants and enhancing the overall stability and integrity of the .au domain space.
[src:australia/au] auDA introduced the ISS in October 2013 as a mandatory requirement, with all accredited registrars required to be certified as ISS compliant within 24 months.
[src:australia/au] The naming rules for .au require registrations under second-level categories that describe a type of entity.
[src:australia/au] *.com.au*, for example, is designed for commercial entities.
[src:australia/au] This follows a similar allocation policy to that formerly used in other countries such as the United Kingdom, Canada and New Zealand.
[src:australia/au] Registrations are currently permitted below a second-level domain, such as "yourname.com.au".
[src:australia/au] In April 2016, auDA announced it would introduce registrations directly at the second level, such as "yourname.au".
[src:australia/au] Direct registrations were due to be implemented in 2017, although an ongoing debate on how cybersquatting would be mitigated led to a delay, with a new launch date of 24 March 2022.
[src:australia/au] Registration of a .au domain is completed through a reseller, known as a registrar, with the registry acting as the wholesale provider. auDA manages domain name policy as the ICANN and Australian Government-endorsed manager of the .au DNS.
[src:australia/au] The .edu.au, .gov.au and .csiro.au namespaces are referred to as "closed" namespaces, since registration is not available to the general public.
[src:australia/au] All other second-level namespaces are referred to as "open" namespaces.
[src:australia/au] According to an annual report filed by .au Domain Association (auDA) in Q4 2022, one in six .au domains were a second-level domain.
[src:australia/au] The direct second-level domain namespace, marketed as ".au Direct" has been made available to the public from 24 March 2022.
[src:australia/au] The .au Direct namespace is intended to complement rather than replace the existing second-level domain namespaces and to provide domain holders with the option to register "shorter, simpler domain names".
[src:australia/au] Unlike the existing second-level domain namespaces, there is no restriction on the domain names that can be registered in the .au Direct namespace, provided the domain name applicant satisfies the Australian presence requirement.
[src:australia/au] In 2019, auDA released a priority implementation policy, whereby existing domain name holders could apply for priority registration of a matching domain name in the new .au Direct namespace.
[src:australia/au] Eligible domain name holders could apply during an allocated sunrise period commencing 24 March 2022 until 20 September 2022.
[src:australia/au] For example, the holders of *domain.com.au*, *domain.org.au* and *domain.net.au* were each eligible to apply for priority registration of *domain.au* during the sunrise period.
[src:australia/au] Where there are two or more Category 1 applications, priority was allocated by agreement between the respective holders, with allocation being placed on hold until consensus is reached or there is only one remaining Category 1 applicant.
[src:australia/au] Where there are two or more Category 2 applications, priority was allocated to the holder with the earliest creation date.
[src:australia/au] Any unclaimed domain names were released to general availability at the end of the sunrise period.
[src:australia/au] These domains were initially managed by the .au Community Domains Trust Archived 6 May 2017 at the Wayback Machine (auCD) on behalf of auDA.
[src:australia/au] The funding of auCD was provided from a ballot of locality names in the .com.au and .net.au domain spaces; previously, any locality with a postcode had been restricted from being registered as a commercial domain name.
[src:australia/au] CGDNs use the state or territory's common abbreviation as the second level of the domain.
[src:australia/au] For example, a community based in Victoria would receive a domain ending in ".vic.au", a Northern Territory community would use ".nt.au", and so on.
[src:australia/au] The third level of the domain must be an addressable locality within that state or territory, of the form "townname.vic.au".
[src:australia/au] Where a name is duplicated within a state – for instance, between a smaller town, and a suburb of a larger town or city — the locality name may be suffixed with the name of the local government area, town or city to which it is associated (e.g.
[src:australia/au] As of November 2009, the auCD site claims 91 active CGDNs across Australia, with a further 115 either approved or awaiting approval.
[src:australia/au] The ".edu.au" is also split up into state-based categories in most cases.
[src:australia/au] auDA has delegated responsibility of the .edu.au domain to Australian Information and Communications Technology in Education Committee (AICTEC), which formed a specialist sub-committee, .edu.au Domain Administration Committee (eDAC).
[src:australia/au] Schools use a domain name that reflect their locale, and these state-based third-level domains are managed independently by the states.
[src:australia/au] For example, a school in Western Australia would register "schoolname.wa.edu.au".
[src:australia/au] Similarly, replacing the state part of these domains, Victoria would use ".vic", Queensland would use ".qld", South Australia would use ".sa", Tasmania would use ".tas", Northern Territory would use ".nt" and the Australian Capital Territory would use ".act".
[src:australia/au] However, after a change of internet services in Queensland State Schools their domain names were changed from "schoolname.qld.edu.au" to "schoolname.eq.edu.au" ("eq" is an abbreviation of the government department name "Education Queensland").
[src:australia/au] This is not the case for private schools in Queensland.
[src:australia/au] Often, domains can even contain a fourth level: for instance, a NSW public school might have the domain "schoolname.schools.nsw.edu.au".
[src:australia/au] Tertiary institutions are typically exempt from requiring state-based distinctions.
[src:australia/au] For example, Edith Cowan University in Western Australia has a domain of "ecu.edu.au" rather than "ecu.wa.edu.au", RMIT University in Victoria uses "rmit.edu.au" rather than "rmit.vic.edu.au".
[src:australia/au] This difference can be associated with states having responsibility for primary and secondary education while the Commonwealth has responsibility for tertiary education; tertiary institutions often having a presence in multiple states.
[src:australia/au] Some second-level domain names are no longer actively used.
[src:australia/au] Whilst registrations are grandfathered for some, no new registrations are accepted.
[src:australia/au] The .au domain namespace has strict licensing and eligibility requirements, compared to other gTLDs.
[src:australia/au] This "policy rich" approach to the name space, begun by Robert Elz and continued by auDA, has meant the .au domain space has avoided the cybersquatting and fraudulent uses of domains prevalent in other more permissive domains.
[src:australia/au] auDA maintains a set of formal published policies and rules which apply to all domains registered in the .au namespace.
[src:australia/au] The *Domain Name Eligibility and Allocation Policy Rules* were first adopted in May 2002.
[src:australia/au] Several revisions were subsequently introduced in 2005, 2008, and 2012 (subsequently updated in 2018).
[src:australia/au] auDA adopted revised rules for domain names in 2021.
[src:australia/au] The new rules (known as the *.au Domain Administration Rules: Licensing*) apply to all domain names created or renewed after 12 April 2021.
[src:australia/au] The new rules provide an "Australian presence" requirement for all domain name holders.
[src:australia/au] To satisfy the Australian presence requirement, an individual must be an Australian permanent resident or citizen, while an organisation must either be incorporated in Australia or hold an Australian Business Number (ABN).
[src:australia/au] Holders of an Australian trade mark also satisfy the Australian presence requirement, provided the domain name is an exact match of the trade mark.
[src:australia/au] Sublicensing of a domain name is prohibited, unless the domain name holder is a parent company of the licensee.
[src:australia/au] Domain name monetisation is prohibited in the .org.au, .asn.au, .id.au and .edu.au and State/Territory geographic namespaces.
[src:australia/au] Domain name disputes between parties are handled under the *.au Dispute Resolution Policy* (*auDRP*), which was adapted from the UDRP by Philip Argy for auDA.
[src:australia/au] The auDRP was adopted in 2016, and applies to all domain names in the Australian open 2LD's registered after 2002.
[src:australia/au] All domain registrants and registrars are contractually required to agree to the auDRP under the terms of registration or accreditation, and are bound by decisions issued by auDRP Dispute Resolution Providers.
[src:australia/au] auDRP complaints are determined by an external accredited dispute resolution provider.
[src:australia/au] The resolution provider is chosen by the complainant.
[src:australia/au] A single domain name dispute may concern one or more Australian domain names.
[src:australia/au] The decision-making panel comprises either a single panelist or three panelists, at the complainant's election.
[src:australia/au] If the complainant elects a single panelist, the respondent (domain holder) may elect to have the proceeding determined by three panelists instead.
[src:australia/au] The decision is made "on the papers" (that is, on the basis of written submissions by the complainant and the respondent) and no hearings are required.
[src:australia/au] Upon lodgement of an auDRP complaint, the domain name's registrar of record is required to impose a registry lock on the domain name until the completion of the proceeding.
[src:australia/au] This is to prevent the respondent from altering or transferring the domain name during the dispute.
[src:australia/au] In addition to the formal auDRP Rules, each Resolution Provider may prescribe Supplemental Rules, relating to their requirements for format of submissions, timing and processes.
[src:australia/au] Panellists are not bound to follow formal rules of evidence, or precedent.
[src:australia/au] However, there are published practice guidelines for auDRP panelists.
[src:australia/au] 3. the respondent has registered *or* used the domain name in bad faith.
[src:australia/au] If a successful decision is issued, then unless Court proceedings are commenced within 10 business days, the remedy is implemented automatically by the domain name's registrar of record without input from the respondent.
[src:australia/au] Decisions issued under the auDRP are published in an archive database.
[src:australia/au] auDA issues an Annual Report as at the end of each financial year (30 June).
[src:australia/au] Since 2019, auDA has also issued quarterly statistical reports.
[src:australia/au] These reports contain statistical information about the performance of the .au domain and other information about auDA's operations during the reporting period.
[src:australia/au] The .com.au second-level domain namespace accounts for the vast majority of domain name registrations.
[src:australia/au] In 2020–21, the number of .com.au domains registered exceeded 3 million for the first time.
[src:australia/au] .au is not the only top-level domain name assigned to Australia.
[src:australia/au] As the appropriate authorities were late in recognising the need to manage these, most were registered by entrepreneurs for use as vanity domains unrelated to the locale they serve. .cc, for example, is now operated by VeriSign. .hm represents a nature preserve with no human inhabitants.
[src:australia/au] Some Australian local government authorities have adopted *.cc domains as a convenient abbreviation for "City Council".
[src:australia/au] For example, the Brisbane City Council uses the domain name "bne.cc" as a URL shortener.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:australia/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:australia/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:australia/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:australia/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:australia/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:australia/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:australia/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:australia/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:australia/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:australia/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:australia/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:australia/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:australia/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:australia/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:australia/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:australia/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:australia/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:australia/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:australia/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:australia/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:australia/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:australia/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:australia/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:australia/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:australia/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:australia/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:australia/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:australia/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:australia/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:australia/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:australia/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:australia/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:australia/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:australia/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:australia/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:australia/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:australia/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:australia/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:australia/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:australia/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:australia/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:australia/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:australia/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:australia/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:australia/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:australia/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:australia/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:australia/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:australia/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:australia/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:australia/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:australia/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:australia/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:australia/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:australia/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:australia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:australia/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:australia/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:australia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:australia/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:australia/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:australia/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:australia/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:australia/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:australia/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:australia/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:australia/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:australia/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:australia/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:australia/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:australia/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:australia/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:australia/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:australia/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:australia/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:australia/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:australia/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:australia/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:australia/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:australia/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:australia/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:australia/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:australia/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:australia/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:australia/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:australia/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:australia/page] The explicitly double-barred (Dollar sign with two vertical lines) sign is called *cifrão* in the Portuguese language.
[src:australia/page] The sign is also used in several compound currency symbols, such as the Brazilian real (R$) and the United States dollar (US$): in local use, the nationality prefix is usually omitted.
[src:australia/page] In countries that have other currency symbols, the US dollar is often assumed and the "US" prefix omitted.
[src:australia/page] The one- and two-stroke versions are often considered mere stylistic (typeface) variants, although in some places and epochs one of them may have been specifically assigned, by law or custom, to a specific currency.
[src:australia/page] The Unicode computer encoding standard defines a single code for both.
[src:australia/page] In most English-speaking countries that use that symbol, it is placed to the left of the amount specified, e.g.
[src:australia/page] The symbol appears in business correspondence in the 1770s from the West Indies referring to the Spanish American peso, also known as "Spanish dollar" or "piece of eight" in British America.
[src:australia/page] The Spanish coins provided the model for the currency that the United States adopted in 1792, and for the larger coins of the new Spanish American republics, such as the Mexican peso, Argentine peso, Peruvian real, and Bolivian sol coins.
[src:australia/page] With the Coinage Act of 1792, the United States Congress created the U.S. dollar, defining it to have "the value of a Spanish milled dollar as the same is now current" but a variety of foreign coins were deemed to be legal tender until the Coinage Act of 1857 ended this status.
[src:australia/page] The earliest U.S. dollar coins did not have any dollar symbol.
[src:australia/page] The first occurrence in print is claimed to be from 1790s, by a Philadelphia printer Archibald Binny, creator of the Monticello typeface.
[src:australia/page] The $1 United States Note issued by the United States in 1869 included a large symbol consisting of a 'U' with the right bar overlapping an 'S' like a single-bar dollar sign, as well as a very small double-stroke dollar sign in the legal warning against forgery *see picture*.
[src:australia/page] It is still uncertain, however, how the dollar sign came to represent the Spanish American peso.
[src:australia/page] The numerous currencies called "dollar" use the dollar sign to express money amounts.
[src:australia/page] The sign is also generally used for the many currencies called "peso" (except the Philippine peso, which uses the symbol "₱").
[src:australia/page] Within a country the dollar/peso sign may be used alone.
[src:australia/page] In other cases, and to avoid ambiguity in international usage, it is usually combined with other glyphs, e.g.
[src:australia/page] Particularly in professional contexts, the unambiguous ISO 4217 three letter code (AUD, MXN, USD, etc.) is preferred.
[src:australia/page] The exception is French-speaking Canada, where the dollar symbol usually appears after the number, the same as the spoken order, e.g., "5 $" for "*cinq dollars*".
[src:australia/page] In Portugal, Brazil, and other parts of the Portuguese Empire, the two-stroke variant of the sign named ***cifrão*** (Portuguese pronunciation: [siˈfɾɐ̃w] ⓘ; plural *cifrões*) has been used as the thousands separator in the national currency, the real (plural "réis", abbreviated "Rs.").
[src:australia/page] For instance, 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)500 would be equivalent to 123500 réis.
[src:australia/page] This usage is attested in 1775, but may be older by a century or more.
[src:australia/page] The cifrão is always written with two vertical lines like (Dollar sign with two vertical lines), and is the official sign of the Cape Verdean escudo (ISO 4217: CVE).
[src:australia/page] In 1911, Portugal redefined the national currency as the escudo, worth 1000 réis, and divided into 100 *centavos*; but the *cifrão* continued to be used as the decimal separator, so that 123(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 123.50 escudos or 123 escudos and 50 centavos.
[src:australia/page] This usage ended in 2002 when the country switched to the euro.
[src:australia/page] Cape Verde, a republic and former Portuguese colony, similarly switched from the real to their local escudo and centavos in 1914, and retains the *cifrão* usage as decimals separator as of 2021.
[src:australia/page] Brazil retained the real and the *cifrão* as thousands separator until 1942, when it switched to the Brazilian cruzeiro, with comma as the decimals separator.
[src:australia/page] The dollar sign, officially with one stroke but often rendered with two, was retained as part of the currency symbol "Cr$", so one would write Cr$13,50 for 13 cruzeiros and 50 centavos.
[src:australia/page] The *cifrão* was formerly used by the Portuguese escudo (ISO: PTE) before its replacement by the euro and by the Portuguese Timor escudo (ISO: TPE) before its replacement by the Indonesian rupiah and the US dollar.
[src:australia/page] In Portuguese and Cape Verdean usage, the *cifrão* is placed as a decimal point between the escudo and *centavo* values.
[src:australia/page] The name originates in the Arabic *ṣifr* (‏صِفْر‎), meaning 'zero'.
[src:australia/page] Outside the Portuguese cultural sphere, the South Vietnamese đồng before 1975 used a method similar to the *cifrão* to separate values of đồng from its decimal subunit *xu*.
[src:australia/page] For example, 7(Dollar sign with two vertical lines)50 meant 7 đồng and 50 xu.
[src:australia/page] In some places and at some times, the one- and two-stroke variants have been used in the same contexts to distinguish between the U.S. dollar and other local currency, such as the former Portuguese escudo.
[src:australia/page] However, such usage is not standardized, and the Unicode specification considers the two versions as graphic variants of the same symbol—a typeface design choice.
[src:australia/page] Computer and typewriter keyboards usually have a single key for that sign, and many character encodings (including ASCII and Unicode) reserve a single numeric code for it.
[src:australia/page] Indeed, dollar signs in the same digital document may be rendered with one or two strokes, if different computer fonts are used, but the underlying codepoint U+0024 (ASCII 3610) remains unchanged.
[src:australia/page] When a specific variant is not mandated by law or custom, the choice is usually a matter of expediency or aesthetic preference.
[src:australia/page] Both versions were used in the US in the 18th century.
[src:australia/page] (An 1861 Civil War-era advertisement depicts the two-stroked symbol as a snake.) The two-stroke version seems to be generally less popular today, though used in some "old-style" fonts like Baskerville.
[src:australia/page] Because of its use in early American computer applications such as business accounting, the dollar sign is almost universally present in computer character sets, and thus has been appropriated for many purposes unrelated to money in programming languages and command languages.
[src:australia/page] The dollar sign "$" has ASCII and Unicode code point U+0024 (in Unicode's Latin-1 block inherited from ASCII).
[src:australia/page] There are no separate encodings for one- and two-line variants.
[src:australia/page] The choice is typeface-dependent; they are allographs.
[src:australia/page] However, there are three other code points that originate from other East Asian standards: the Taiwanese small form variant, the CJK fullwidth form, and the Japanese emoji.
[src:australia/page] The glyphs for these code points are typically larger or smaller than the primary code point, but the difference is mostly aesthetic or typographic, and the meanings of the symbols are the same.
[src:australia/page] However, for usage as the special character in various computing applications (see following sections), U+0024 is typically the only code that is recognized.
[src:australia/page] Support for the two-line variant varies.
[src:australia/page] As of 2019, the Unicode standard considers the distinction between one- and two-bar dollar signs a stylistic distinction between fonts, and has no separate code point for the *cifrão*.
[src:australia/page] The symbol is not in the October 2019 "pipeline", though it has been requested formally.
[src:australia/page] In LaTeX, with the textcomp package installed, the *cifrão* ((Dollar sign with two vertical lines)) can be input using the command `\textdollaroldstyle`.
[src:australia/page] However, because of font substitution and the lack of a dedicated code point, the author of an electronic document who uses one of these fonts intending to represent a *cifrão* cannot be sure that every reader will see a double-bar glyph rather than the single barred version.
[src:australia/page] Because of the continued lack of support in Unicode, a single bar dollar sign is frequently employed in its place even for official purposes.
[src:australia/page] Where there is any risk of misunderstanding, the ISO 4217 three-letter acronym is used.
[src:australia/page] The character U+3326 ㌦ SQUARE DORU is a squared word version of ドル (*doru* "dollar", in Japanese).
[src:australia/page] The character U+5F17 弗 CJK UNIFIED IDEOGRAPH-5F17 has been formerly repurposed as a symbol for dollars in Japan because of its visual similarity.
[src:australia/page] The symbol is sometimes used derisively, in place of the letter S, to indicate greed or excess money such as in "Micro$oft", "Di$ney", "Chel$ea" and "GW$"; or supposed overt Americanization as in "$ky".
[src:australia/page] The dollar sign is also used intentionally to stylize names such as A$AP Rocky, Ke$ha, and Ty Dolla $ign or words such as ¥€$.
[src:australia/page] In 1872, Ambrose Bierce referred to California governor Leland Stanford as $tealand Landford.
[src:australia/page] In Scrabble notation, a dollar sign is placed after a word to indicate that it is valid according to the North American word lists, but not according to the British word lists.
[src:australia/page] A dollar symbol is used as unit of reactivity for a nuclear reactor, 0 $ being the threshold of slow criticality, meaning a steady reaction rate, while 1 $ is the threshold of prompt criticality, which means a nuclear excursion or explosion.
[src:australia/page] In the 1993 version of the Turkmen Latin alphabet $ was used as a transliteration of the Cyrillic letter Ш, in 1999 was replaced by the letter Ş.
